<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-323-324  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 323 324.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  April 1990 v13 n4 p52(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PACS: a premature paradise. (Pictorial Archiving andCommunications Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Freiherr, Greg.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Graphical networks known as Pictorial Archiving and CommunicationsSystems (PACS) are computerizing radiology by enhancing medicalimages and linking them with patient data.andP;  At least 100 companiesare building and integrating PACS components.andP;  Most applicationsof full-sized PACS have been in major teaching institutions, butwidespread acceptance of such total systems has been hindered bytechnical and political considerations.andP;  Although PACS enhanceproductivity, they bring no revenue, and insurance companies areunlikely to pay for their use.andP;  Communication technology andadequate software for managing the sheer volume of data that needsprocessing with PACS have also curtailed their widespreadacceptance.andP;  Vendors such as Philips-ATandamp;T, Vortech Data Inc, andSophy Medical systems have begun offering mini-PACS products thatperform valuable data capture, networking, display and storagetasks as alternatives and building blocks to full-blown systems.andO;These are easy to learn and use and offer immediate benefits.andO;Teleradiology, which enables transmission of images to remotesites, is a good example of an element of PACS that can also standon its own.andP;  Interand, Image Data, Data Span and Advanced VideoProducts Inc all offer portable, affordable teleradiologyproducts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     RadiologyComputer SystemsNetworksComputer GraphicsMedical DiagnosisImaging Technology.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>